titlepage.author: Able Ramirez

did.head: Descriptive Summary
did.abstract: Records and activities of the U Ranch and the McEntire family of Sterling County, Texas.

repository.label: Repository:
repository.corpname: Southwest Collection/Special Collections Library, Texas Tech University

did.physdesc: 51 boxes and 2 oversized ledgers (53.0 linear feet)

bioghist.head: Biographical Sketch
bioghist.p: The U Ranch, comprised of 18 sections, is located 10 miles northwest of Sterling City in Sterling County, Texas. The ranch was founded by Col. W. R. McEntire, a Civil War Confederate Veteran, when he acquired the land from M. B. Stephenson in 1880. Over the years the ranch grew from 15 sections to 150 sections. Some of the land was passed down to the children of W. R. McEntire. George received title to 23,000 acres in 1906. Each of his children, George H., Jr. and Virginia, inherited 16,233 acres in 1962. Virginia ran the ranch under the name VJ Ranch while George H. McEntire, Jr. called his the U Ranch. In 1999, the ranch was owned by Ruth Caldwell, the daughter of George H. McEntire, Jr. Her son Chris manages the sheep and cattle ranch for the family.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The collection contains correspondence, legal materials, financial materials, and scrapbook material that detail the activities of the U Ranch from the late 19th Century to the 1960s. Included are materials on W. R. McEntire, a Civil War veteran and rancher, George H. McEntire, Sr., and George H. McEntire, Jr. Additionally, there are photocopies of U Ranch records archived at the University of Texas. Transferred were artifacts, sound recordings, and photographs.
